0071|- [HelpText]
0072|*When printing tables in proportional pitch the problem is, how to keep
0073|*the columns correctly aligned.
0074|*In the PRINT operation control lines having a 'T' in the control column
0075|*serve this purpose. A 'T' line must have other 'T's to indicate the
0076|*columns (tab positions) which should be aligned in the final output.
0077|*After encountering a 'T' line PRINT will align all subsequent lines
0078|*according to it. To supress the effect of the 'T' line for the remain-
0079|*ing lines, an empty 'T' line (with no 'T's except in the control column)
0080|*must be used.
0081|*Any 'T' on 'T' line indicates the text to be aligned to the right and
0082|*parentheses () indicate alignment to the left from ')'.
0083|*To change the tabular alignment, a new 'T' line should be included
0084|*and to supress tabulating temporarily, 'U' should be used in the control
0085|*column. For example:
0086|* 11 T   T          (     )    ( )  T
0087|* 12 *   January    1000.45    112  good
0088|* 13 *   February    987.87     55  poor
0089|* 14 U This line will be printed without alignment.
0090|* 15 *   March      1245.09     65  satisfactory
0091|* 16 T Here is a line (without capital t) terminating alignment.
0092|* 17 * Lines 12,13 and 15 will be correctly aligned according to 11.
0094|*The gaps between the columns indicated by 'T's and parentheses on the
0095|*'T' line are selected according to the current font size.
0096|*The default gap is 60% of the font size in points.
0097|*This often leads to gaps which are too wide for numeric tables,
0098|*for example. In such cases the gap may be changed by entering
0099|*the 'T' line in the form
0100|*    T    *8    T     (      )     (   )   T
0101|*where the number (8) after '*' indicates the new gap in points.
